---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import NewsletterSignup from '../components/NewsletterSignup.astro';
---

<Layout
  title="About"
  description="Why we started A Green Family — and what we believe about sustainable living for real families."
>
  <article class="max-w-2xl mx-auto px-6 py-14">

    <!-- Header -->
    <header class="mb-10 text-center">
      <p class="text-6xl mb-4">🌿</p>
      <h1 class="font-serif text-4xl text-forest mb-3">About A Green Family</h1>
      <p class="text-ink-muted text-lg leading-relaxed">
        A family trying to do better. Not perfectly. Just better than before.
      </p>
    </header>

    <!-- Story section -->
    <div class="prose prose-green prose-lg max-w-none">

      <p>
        My wife grew up on a small farm in the interior. Her family came from European immigrants — people who had crossed an ocean and built something from not very much, and who treated waste the way most people treat theft: as something that simply didn't happen. Food scraps went to the chickens or the compost heap. Clothes were mended, handed down, and eventually cut into rags. The jars that came in from the market went back into the pantry with something else in them. There was no recycling bin. There wasn't much need for one.
      </p>
      <p>
        My upbringing was similar, if a little less tidy about it. Cooking on a wood stove. A garden that produced most of what we ate through the summer. A grandmother who would have been genuinely puzzled by the idea of buying a new shirt when the old one was still wearable, or of throwing away a glass jar that still had twenty years of use left in it.
      </p>
      <p>
        We moved, finished school, started careers, had kids, and at some point — without really deciding to — we became a family that bought a lot and thought about it very little. The plastic bags accumulated under the sink. The paper towel roll replaced itself every two weeks. The kids went through clothes at a rate that didn't seem possible. We weren't wasteful people, exactly. We'd just stopped paying attention.
      </p>
      <p>
        What changed it, honestly, was money. We started tracking what we spent on things that got used once and thrown away — paper towels, plastic wrap, zip-lock bags, water bottles, the fast-fashion school clothes that were worn out by February — and the number was embarrassing. Not enormous, but embarrassing in the way that small, avoidable things are embarrassing when you add them up. And once we started looking at it that way, we couldn't really stop.
      </p>
      <p>
        The solutions we landed on weren't new to us. Composting. Cloth instead of disposable. Secondhand before new. Cooking from scratch with actual ingredients. Growing a few things on the windowsill. These are things we grew up with, things our grandmothers did without thinking, things that got categorised somewhere along the way as either old-fashioned or as belonging to a particular type of person we didn't feel like we were. But they work. And it turns out they're not that hard.
      </p>
      <p>
        We're four people, a dog, a house in the Seattle suburbs, two cars — one electric, one not yet. We cook Latin food most nights, we're still figuring out composting in a place that gets eight months of rain, and we still have a roll of paper towels in the cabinet for the situations that are genuinely disgusting. This site isn't coming from a place of having worked it all out. It's coming from a place of being partway through and finding it worth talking about.
      </p>
      <p>
        Every article here is about something we've actually done, in this house, with these kids, on a normal budget. When a product genuinely helped us, we mention it — some of those links are affiliate links, which means we earn a small commission if you buy through them. It doesn't change what we recommend. You can read the full <a href="/disclosure">disclosure here</a> if you want the details.
      </p>
      <p>
        If something here is useful to you, that's what it's for. And if you have a tip or a question or something that works in your house that we haven't covered, write to us at <a href="mailto:hello@agreenfamily.com">hello@agreenfamily.com</a>. We read everything.
      </p>

    </div>

    <!-- Newsletter -->
    <NewsletterSignup />

  </article>
</Layout>
